passages.text: 2Q25 - Strong PPOP growth beat expectation

2Q25 Beat - BoNJ's 2Q25 PPOP (+13% y/y) and profits (+11% y/y) beat JPMe by 10%/8%, respectively. Strong PPOP growth was driven by robust NII growth (+27%y/y), milder-than- expected non- fee contraction (- 3% y/y) and improvement in cost efficiency, while the fee income came in slightly below our estimation. In addition, we like BoNB's stable asset quality and improved capital positions in the 2Q result. However, more significant h/h NIM contraction in 1H25 (- 6bps h/h) vs 2H24 (- 4bps h/h) might disappoint some investors. On net, this is a strong result, and we expect a positive share price reaction.

- Solid NII growth beat expectation. 2Q NII (+27% y/y) beat JPMe by 18%. In detail, the interest income increased by +8% y/y, aided by strong interest earning assets growth of 18% y/y. Meanwhile, interest expense declined by -1% y/y, which we believe was a result of effective liability structure optimization and funding cost management.

- Non-fee income contraction was milder than expected. 2Q25 non-fee income contracted by -3% y/y. On a semi-annual basis, 1H25 non-fee decreased by -7% y/y, which is milder than our expectation considering the weak bond market in 1H25.

- Asset quality remained largely stable. 2Q25 NPL ratio slightly picked up by 1bps q/q, while the SML ratio decreased by -9bps q/q, indicating an improving AQ outlook. Overdue loan ratio stayed flat h/h in 1H25. Corporate AQ stayed solid, with 1H25 corporate NPL % dropping by -1bps h/h. Retail NPL % increased by 14bps h/h, which is better than city bank peers who have released results (BoNB +18bps h/h, BoHZ +22bps h/h). Management disclosed that the NPL % of personal consumption loans and personal business loans increased in 1H25 vs 2H24, while that of credit card loans dropped.

- Marginal improvement in capital adequacy ratio, yet below expectation: In 2Q25, the company's CET-1 ratio/Tier-1 ratio/capital adequacy ratio were 9.47%/11.07%/13.63%, respectively, up 58/55/61 bps. BoNJ's CB conversion into equities in 2Q25 helped improve its capital level. BoNJ announced it will distribute an interim dividend in 2025, but there are no further details in the 1H25 report.

- 1H25 NIM contracted by -6bps h/h. Magnitude of NIM contraction in 1H25 was larger vs 2H24 (-4bps h/h). The contraction was due to deterioration in asset structure, in our view. Daily average volume of

Looking into yield details, 1H25 asset yield declined by 22bps h/h, mainly dragged by a 30bps h/h decrease in debt investment yield. On the liability side, funding cost also decreased by -22bps h/h in 1H. Loan-deposit spread stayed flat h/h in 1H25.

- Bank of Nanjing offers an attractive shareholder return, and the dividend payout ratio is guaranteed to be maintained at above \(30\%\) , as per a long-term commitment stated in the company's Articles of Association.- BoNJ's revenue structure is biased towards non-fee income, which mainly constitutes investment income from bond trading. The revenue structure is subject to higher uncertainty, in our view.- Credit risks remain another concern in the near term with increasing NPL formation ratio. We remain cautious on the credit risk outlook due to the bank's expansionary strategy on consumption loans amid a weak macro.- NIM pressure persists, owing to BoNB's higher deposit cost and hefty corporate lending.
Our Dec- 25 price target of Rmb11.40 is based on a DDM, assuming a cost of equity of \(13.4\%\) , normalized ROE of \(10.5\%\) and terminal date of 31 Dec 2027.
